The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and issued a brochure
Women who are branded witches in Burkina Faso usually have some common social characteristics.
They rather belong to the older generation, they find no work - for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
When one of these women becomes a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
"Men are rarely affected by this fate."
“Young and healthy women, too, are spared as they help with work and give birth to children,” a nurse describes the situation that takes care of more than one hundred women expelled from their communities in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso in a specialty home.
The local government now decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And for this reason, he issued a brochure to stop the "witch pursuit."
But the thing has a catch.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," the newspaper "derStandard" pointed out the dilemma of written enlightenment.
But being accused of witchcraft is also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighbouring Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahov<0xC3><0xA1> was tortured to death by three women and two men - they poured petroleum into her and simply lit her.
This incident was also reported by the BBC.
However, the perpetrators claimed that the matter was only a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to their version, oil is ignited, which is used for ritual anointing.
After the group tried to “expel an evil spirit” from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" supports people here without regard to their education.
"The Standard" quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso: "Women of human souls are a danger earlier than today," he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to defuse the witch hunt, last year the Gambian president himself did a decent job.
"President Yahya Jammeh sparked a monstrous witch hunt after his aunt's death, as they allegedly had a share in their deaths and would now try to kill the president himself by black magic."
"He called for shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by policemen, soldiers and the President's bodyguard, kidnapped indiscriminately detained women and men from Gambian villages and took them to the President's farm in Kanilai," Amnesty International said in a statement.
On the farm, the imprisoned people were forced to drink absud from plants with hallucinogenic effects, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested people did not survive the stay on the farm.
It was only because of international pressure that nearly a thousand prisoners were released.
