The architects saw in - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with everything that goes with it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini-playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design staff since last year.
The design and architecture office Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of well-known Brno buildings originate, calculated from the first designs for the new Avriopoint building with the premises for its company mini-kindergarten.
As a wise expectation, most of his 90 employees (inside) are in the baby boom age and the company is concerned that the projectants and architects return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Along with the ability to work shortened, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for civil engineers to bring their demanding profession and child care together.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of the staff of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The in-house mini-kindergarten is funded by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from the European Social Fund and from the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (subsidies amounting to CZK 2,8 million) the necessary facilities and equipment have been procured and qualified personnel and operations have been provided for a period of 2 years.
After spending the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the mini-kindergarten for 3 more years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the application process.
Fully qualified staff takes care of the children - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children can be present at the same time, but the day alternates over several children.
The kindergarten is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights with regard to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and nursing, the program content in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the supporting program of preschool education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, by the way they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus avoid the stress of late picking up the children from a faraway kindergarten.
Parents use their working hours more productively.
It is no wonder that there are also natural and loyal employer-employee relationships.
Arch.Design was thus among the Czech companies that offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and through such programs strengthen their personal marketing.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn up fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms got the nickname "bone house".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splinters and mosaics, the shed-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi’s Art Nouveau style.
The fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only upon closer inspection that one notices that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the entire fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade looks even more plastic, more dramatic and the special lighting enhances the shine of the colors.
The same swinging lines and twisted shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even look holes and strips.
The Batll<0xC3><0xB3> House in the Eixample district on the bustling shopping street Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA1>cia No. 43 was built by the reconstruction of an 1877 house by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but in the end he agreed to Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> apartment building was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner were created and also the use of mosaics on the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade was his idea.
However, numerous other painters and artists also collaborated on the design of the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s Casa Mil<0xC3><0xA1> in the Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given the nickname "bone house" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others, on the other hand, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "yawning house".
It is also said that at the top of the building, the sword of St. George, the patron of Catalonia, was depicted.
But also other sculptural elements symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed the house with a unique central heating system with venting ducts and typical fireplaces.
A bit bizarre already appears her 45-degree inclination.
In his work, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> consistently ignored all the building regulations of the time and was in no way fooled by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he gave about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so horrified at the conclusion two years later that they demanded a remedy.
The councillors also objected, among other things, to the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no more changes, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the district's request to do so, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> made a request to authorize the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor was a social salon, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building passes through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with a modern concept for the interconnection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could chat comfortably without having to give up a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, the house received a rather unusual roof and two further floors through Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s renovation.
Also impressive is Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s play with the light, as well as the blue and white glazed tiles, with which the courtyard is clad and the light courtyards.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house the highest level of light.
In doing so, he simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which absorb sunlight on the contrary.
The House Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made available to the public.
The homeowners only decided in the year to take this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were kept, yes, they were also extended to other common areas and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard stick, it is 16.50 Euro, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist IDs get a 20% discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, you should try to make friendship with one of the house dwellers and visit him at home.
The right mattress and bed grate? Women have different desires than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the lying area - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
However, these must be complemented harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
When choosing, many things play a role - the weight, the size, the state of health and, last but not least, the sex of the sleeper.
Equally important is the interior in which mattress and rust have to be subordinated.
Typical example?
In a weekend home where it is not heated regularly, latex mattresses are not well suited, as they take much longer to "warm up".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned on a regular basis.
If they do not have enough venting ducts in the core and are also lying on a solid plate, moisture accumulates: it is therefore not impossible to form under their mold.
Of course, the choice also plays a role in what you are used to.
Those who have been abroad for a long time, where very high soft-layer mattresses are common, will find it difficult to get used to a low-lying mattress with a hard surface.
"Well, all the ice hockey players who came back from the NHL complained to me that they can't sleep right here."
"For their shaved shoulders, heels and hips, they simply need a soft layer of visco foam (Memory Foam - a shape memory polymer)."
"I recommend these, among other things, also sugar-sick people who suffer from a disorder of the nervous system, so that they can poorly receive the "information" from the joints and the skin," explains Sylva Hadamczikov<0xC3><0xA1>, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That’s why years ago I bought many ice hockey players, but also other customers these mattresses with visco-foam (Memory Foam).
"Today this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses are offered by the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico."
And you don’t necessarily have to be a famous ice hockey player to appreciate the benefits of the Visco foam.
This “miracle” actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it nestles against the warm body.
Nowhere does it press, in the night you do not roll around like after a heavy fight.
You just sleep a lot better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against decubitus (wound burn).
When choosing the mattress size, you should still add the length of the soles of the feet to the height, i.e. about 21 to 34 cm.
Man and woman, who are 180 cm tall, need a 210 to 220 cm long bed.
Each sleeper should have at least 90 cm of reclining width, i.e. 180 cm together.
For single beds, for example for singles, 120 to 140 cm are attached.
For the sake of comfort and also for possible visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal bed width: "If you lie on your back, there should still be enough space for the slightly angled arms", advises Ing. Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>, the guild master of upholsterers and room furnishers, who has been dedicating herself for years to the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture and who also lectures this topic in specialist schools.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own grate and mattress, but be careful when shopping so that the mattresses are equally high.
Otherwise, nothing else is left but to mount the grates at different heights and this is not possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with spring skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters should be on the molding layer and the fine pad.
“You can’t feel the feathers with your hand or when you sit down,” warns Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Each mattress requires a special rust type.
Fully padded beds with mattress and underlay such as co-grown siam twins have nothing to look for in the bedroom.
These mattresses cannot be ventilated and the cover cannot be washed, which is already happening today.
And since you lose between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years, the mattress slowly becomes a huge (and clogged) sieve.
This is also why experts reject advertising slogans that promise a lifespan of up to 25 years, even a lifetime warranty for mattresses.
Every thing has its ifs and buts.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: for mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width, one should not shy away from the hygiene of the washable, removable covers, however, it is recommended to use a mattress protector, which can be easily removed and washed.
Even though mattress covers are usually made with all-round zipper, so that you get two halves after opening (immensly important for the washing process and the washing machine size!), the manipulation with larger mattresses, especially on their own, often seems like the unequal fight between David and Goliath.
Do you have a solid plate in bed instead of a grate?
Get out of here!
Or at most for a bed for unloved guests and for a single night.
Also, they should rather provide the plate with ventilation holes (if there are no in it) and use mattresses with spring skeleton and 15 cm minimum height with so-called pocket spring core and fine cushions.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a base.
Latex or sandwich mattresses are suitable for non-adjustable slatted slats with 14 to 18 slatted slats (laminates) (possibly also combinations of latex and coconut), always pay off slats with a greater number of slats, i.e. from 28 and more slatted slats, with lumbar support in the lumbar vortex area and the possibility to regulate the slat hardness.
Adjustable slatted grates do not include spring-skeleton mattresses, as they do not react to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the spring strips, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This concerns a special fastening of the spring strips, which makes it possible to press the spring strips or even to be angled in such a way that they allow the pointed sinking of the shoulder of the sleeper.
Especially for men with wide shoulders an important thing.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have begun to use soft zones for the shoulder area in "men's mattresses".
The ladies are also thought of - they are treated to these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point-elastic wing spring systems (lattoflex) or grates with point-elastic contact pads with so-called multitorsion suspension are intended.
The pressure is distributed over several points, which reduces the voltage.
But - if you use a bad (too large and full) pillow to the right mattress and right rust, most of the benefits are lost again.
Here, too, a rule of thumb: the pillow should support the head, its tips should only reach to the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Ideally, a pillow of 50 x 60 cm, as the Scandinavians like, for example, appears.
In the side position, the pillow (together with the shoulder relief zone in the grate or the soft zone in the mattress) should balance the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the former (filled with hay) straw sacks.
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least their admixtures.
Also with mattresses, the new magic word is "Bio".
Instead of petroleum raw materials, natural oils - for example castor and soybean oils - are increasingly used for the production of polyurethane foams.
Soybean is probably used by all well-known manufacturers.
"Bio means that in mattresses, their core consists of materials of pure natural origin," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1><0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek of the company Tropico Plus.
However, natural materials are also used in the production of mattress covers - one of the first was aloe vera.
However, you can also treat yourself to microcapsules that spread fresh forest or lavender scent while sleeping.
Here, too, you make a difference between a man and a woman.
While men use a "cooling" plant extract from birch leaves so that the mattress cover can absorb the heat and cool the body, the covers for women have "warming" effect.
Extracts from red peppers stimulate blood circulation, so the weaker sex gets comfortable warm when sleeping.
What about today's favorites?
Cold foam mattresses (it has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercially available polyurethane and also much more flexible).
