The Democratic Routine
The democratic movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
These results were obtained by the Latinobar<0xC3><0xB3>metro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly evident in this year’s September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its most important institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of democracy advocates rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Such a trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the sharp slump last year.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region’s most populous countries, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see diagram 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents stated that they were satisfied with the democratic practice of their country, which is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Diagram 3).
Approximately 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined the efforts for more democracy.
The fact that this continued during the global economic crisis may be due to the fact that the countries of Latin America experienced only a short period of recession and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were caught up by a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and has fallen by 32% this year.)
However, there are strong differences in mood from country to country (see diagram 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of the outgoing president Luiz In<0xC3><0xA1>cio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread thought of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
For the second time since the start of the survey, many respondents in Latin America see a bigger problem in crime in their country than in unemployment (see diagram 5).
Approximately 31% say that either they or a family member have been victims of a crime in the past year, but compared to 38% in the last year, the figures have fallen, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
Increasing economic output is reflected in the stronger support for the private and market economy: about 71% of respondents supraregionally stated that the private sector is indispensable for development, while in 2007 it was 56% (see diagram 6).
Approximately 58% said that only the market economy can make progress for their country, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of Venezuelans have maintained this view (and 80% are for a private sector), although their left-wing president, Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, nationalized many private companies.
Brazil has the largest weight in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, on the other hand, see the US as the most influential country, with this role being taken over by Venezuela in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
An electoral slap
No one expected the elections to be perfect in Haiti on November 28.
But the facts far outweighed the fears of the electoral helpers who rushed to help the shattered country.
Overcrowded ballot boxes, multiple votes, ballot papers in the gutter, destroyed polling stations and intimidations were only part of the problems.
Electoral offices opened with hours of delay.
Many Haitians, many of whom had become homeless as a result of the January earthquake, strove around in search of a choice.
Some finally gave up completely.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some suspected leaders, demanded the abolition of election results due to an alleged fraud.
There were some violent protests across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the head of the UN mission in Haiti, called the election "quite good in many respects."
According to a cautious statement by observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, "these irregularities, however serious they may be, do not necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show goes on.
The election authority, allegedly committed to the unpopular outgoing president René Préval and his candidate, Jude Célestin, will announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The expected election is scheduled for January.
There is still hope in the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, rap musician Michel Martelly and former first lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial invalidity suit.
If Jude Célestin, who finds little or no agreement with the electorate, is declared the winner of the run-off election by the electorate, this could lead to problems.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million of the earthquake victims still live in tents, low turnout was feared.
On Election Day, many Haitians were prevented from voting due to a lack of organization.
Shortly before the start of the election, about 250,000 ID cards needed for the election had not yet been issued.
There's a lot at stake.
The donor countries see a legitimate, recognized government as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
The Haitians themselves are of the same opinion.
Secretly in the middle
In the weeks following her husband’s sudden death, Argentina’s president, Cristina Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez, experienced a wave of sympathy that boosted her popularity rate by 20 points to over 50%, the highest since her election in 2007.
However, whether this will help you re-election next year depends on whether the visibly mourning Cristina Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez is more willing to compromise than her deceased husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who also directed economic policy after his wife’s election, often drew up budgets that did not fully reflect tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
