Taiwan voters are slowly approaching a closer connection to the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother beyond the strait?
On November 27, more than 7.5 million voters, that is 70% of all eligible voters, set out to elect mayors and councillors in the five districts, which is seen as a broad assessment of President Ma Ying-jeou.
Through the establishment of groundbreaking business relations, including a partial free trade agreement, Ma herself is a symbol of relations with the mainland. His policy has changed the relationship with the Chinese motherland for the first time since 1949.
Ma passed the exam, but barely.
Although his Kuomintang Party (KMT) represents three of the five mayors, it received no majority of votes.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which advocates greater independence of Taiwan, received almost 50% of the vote, the KMT received 45%.
In the case of a presidential election, this would have been a problem for Ma.
Since his election two years ago, his party’s share of votes has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the DPP even moved into the city councils together with the KMT.
During the election there were events common in Taiwan such as truck convoys with rioters, flag-swinging mass parades and only sparsely dressed dancers.
There was even the obligatory, mysterious murder attempt.
Sean Lien, the son of Lien Chan and honorary chairman of the KMT, gave a speech to a KMT candidate on the eve of the election.
When a man shot him in the face from the crowd, Lien was wounded and a nearby spectator was killed.
Bizarrely, it is not clear whether the shooter wanted to kill Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
Regardless, according to Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the DPP, the attack has affected the election and put the DPP in a bad light, which has given the KMT more votes.
Perhaps China was the biggest winner of the campaign.
Interestingly, relations with the mainland were not discussed.
Instead, candidates debated plans for social housing and job creation.
The Taiwanese love their factual independence and reject China’s military threat.
For this reason, the KMT does not like to put its relations with the government in Beijing in the foreground.
But this time the DPP also avoided too much stirring up the anti-Chinese feelings.
She reacted to the new awareness that Taiwan’s economy cannot survive without China.
Ma, for his part, wants to be confirmed that the majority of Taiwanese support his China policy.
The Beijing government will continue to pursue its strategy of luring Taiwan back into the Community with economic incentives.
China immediately sent a negotiator to Taipei to prepare for a summit on investment security and medical cooperation.
It certainly also wants political integration, but the most important thing first.
It is better to wait until after the 2012 presidential election.
The DPP has now reinvented itself.
Two years ago, she was severely weakened: former party leader Chen Shui-bian was imprisoned for corruption.
During his presidency from 2000 to 2008, he vehemently advocated absolute independence.
But under Tai’s reign, a new generation of moderate politicians developed and the DPP is fighting for the voices of the working class and the youth.
Tsai, as the DPP’s presidential candidate, found great approval, such as Su Tseng-chang under Chen.
Her party is now doing everything possible to show that she, too, is able to build close relations with Beijing.
Tsai is planning an idea-forge as a point of contact between the DPP and China, but this requires prejudicial discussions.
Tsai publicly stated that her party offered a “trustworthy alternative” to Mas’s premature rapprochement with China.
Chen seems very upset about this change.
From his cell, he stated that the DPP candidates would have done better at insisting on Taiwan’s independence.
He even called on the pragmatist Su to renounce the presidential candidacy.
Even without Chen’s interference, the DPP finds it difficult to choose its potential candidate.
The KMT will have to undergo its own self-analysis.
Mas’s values are poor, despite rapid economic growth; the KMT candidates wanted to run their election campaign without him.
The main reasons for his unpopularity seem to be unemployment and the ever-increasing gap between rich and poor.
