Police operations in China are becoming more gentle
Like a training officer, Tang Shenbin walked across an urban square, checked his nervous subordinates, and gave orders with military authority and muted voice.
He wanted his female members of the Chengguan – China’s robust guards of urban order, feared and despised for their arbitrary raids and their craving for violence – to impress the spectators.
"Still standing!"
"Look straight!"
"Show them," he whispered, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls, barely outgrown the teenage age, with white gloves and identical olive green jackets and pants stood firm.
Four pairs of black pumps were in a straight line.
Four neat hats sat perfectly on the hair with blue and white striped bows.
"To me, they look average," Mr. Tang remarks disdainfully.
“Models are pretty.”
Several governments have already tried to polish up the image of China’s city inspectors.
In a city, all new applicants must have a university degree.
The province of Guangdong introduced a bright blue uniform instead of the grey-green one.
Wuhan in Central China replaced violence with staring: In 2009, 50 officials reportedly circumnavigated an improperly set up snack car and stared at the operator until it packed in after half an hour and left the square.
Xindu, a city district in Chengdu with 680,000 inhabitants, wants to fundamentally change the image.
Since 2003, 13 women have been reinforcing the urban police strips. They have been specially selected for their appearance, their good figure and their youth.
They are supposed to give the coarse police a softer, feminine aspect.
But unfortunately Scarlett Johansson would hardly be able to improve the bad image the Chinese have of these city commands.
Rightly so, critics.
Unlike the police, these officials are only allowed to enforce urban laws using fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media routinely shows a different picture.
In January 2008, officials in Hubei Province beat a spectator to death when he filmed them with his cell phone as they beat down a protest action against a garbage dump.
Last year, a training manual of Beijing officials was stolen and published on the Internet, describing how to beat offenders without bloodshed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon trader suffered brain injuries after a handout with five officials.
A violent video game that can be downloaded from the Internet shows China-trained officials in an attack on street traffickers.
"Chengguan scares the government," China Daily lamented last year after further controversy over tactics.
The newspaper called for a “really thorough cleanup.”
Skeptics believe the current approach is insufficient.
When the district searched eight female recruits by advertisement in October, an editorial in the Beijing Evening News asked whether the women had real tasks or should only serve as optical distraction.
Probably both.
According to the job advertisement, women between the ages of 18 and 22 were sought with a good figure and "harmonious facial features".
They should be above average in size - about 1.5m or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
The employment relationship ends at the age of 26.
According to the officials, the work for women over 25 is too physically exhausting.
"The most important thing is their image," said an unnamed district official on the quasi-government website Rednet.com.
"Whether the candidates get the job depends first on their external appearance, such as size, weight, facial features, etc."
Then comes temperament and "inner qualities".
“Female Chengguans are like flower vases,” he said, adding, “but beyond that, they have other duties.”
Zheng Lihua, deputy head of the district's municipal administration, would not agree to this description,
But admitted that in China sizing requirements in job advertisements are not uncommon for both sexes.
The same applies to uniform facial features.
Whether this should be equated with good looks is controversial in China.
But people with disabilities or physical disfigurements do not need to apply.
"Unfortunately, we can't use cripples or buckles here," said Mr. Zheng.
“Your image would not be good.”
Liu Yi, who patrols in Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22, has apple pies and a well-shaped mouth.
She did not feel as sexist that so much importance is placed on her appearance.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asks with an ironic look.
Her colleague with the dimples, 21-year-old Xu Yang, commented, "We have the task of representing the image of the city."
According to them, they do not regret the brief attitude, as they have more ambitious career plans than just shying traders through the alleys to prevent them from doing business.
Every morning, the strip deals with about twelve street dealers who try to sell as many buns and tofu dishes as possible on foot or on a bicycle before being chased away.
"Mr. Wang, please get out of here."
"We have told you this so many times!" explains Frl. Xu to a dealer who had fled on foot and had temporarily abandoned his pasta kitchen attached to a bicycle cart.
According to the officials, the activity is more monotonous than strenuous.
"It's almost the same every day," explains Huang Jing, 20, who studies in leisure sales.
"All routine."
One reason for this is that the female officials are not allowed to confiscate the goods of the traders, like their male colleagues.
They can only threaten offenders to report them to their male superiors.
This is to protect them from public hostilities, which officials in China are often exposed to.
This year, hundreds of residents of Kunming, the capital of Yunnan Province, ransacked after rumours circulated that Chengguan officials had killed a trader.
More than a dozen police officers and Chenguan officials were injured in the nightly incident, 14 government vehicles were toppled or set on fire.
Xindu has so far been spared such violence.
But unrest cannot be ruled out.
Just two blocks away from the quiet Baonguang Square, where the female officials patronized that morning, over 50 people gathered at a street corner.
Officials had confiscated a motorcycle that was repaired against the regulations on the sidewalk instead of in a workshop.
The owner shouted Zeter and Mordio.
After 15 minutes of hesitation, the officers paved their way to their vehicles with a grim face and continued with the motorcycle and its owner.
Li Xuedong, 40, a male strip coordinator, remained behind, turning his white nameplate to remain anonymous.
Like their colleagues, the coordinators - men over 40 - play a purely supportive role.
But they were not trained to present a clean image.
“Sometimes we go verbally.”
"Sometimes, but also physically," Mr. Li explains soberly.
“Most of the time, people start arguing.”
