The Justice Department did not want to comment on the case.
The verdict was a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, and in their opinion there was sufficient evidence that Ensign disregarded the ban on lobbying.
Interviews, emails, and other documents first revealed in the New York Times in October 2009 gave rise to the suspicion that Ensign Douglas Hampton, one of his constituents, helped to lucrative orders to buy his silence over an affair with Hampton's wife Cynthia.
Cynthia Hampton served as treasurer during an election campaign of Ensigns.
Ensign contacted some political friends to get Hampton to work, and according to the documents and interrogations, he took over lobbying for them after hiring Hampton.
Since Hampton was recently still in Ensign's electoral team, he was not allowed to lobby for his former employer or the entire Senate for a year.
According to ethics experts, the unusual agreement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, violated the so-called ban on turning-door lobby.
According to the published evidence, "it seems to be a deal and a violation of the revolving door statutes," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients who are aimed at the government.
While the Department of Justice officially refused to disclose the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other Ethiopian lawyers said the ministry appears to be very cautious in picking up political charges after a variety of defeats prosecuted by the media with great interest, including last year’s decision to drop the charge against former Senator Ted Stevens for misconduct on the part of the state prosecutor.
Prosecutors are “obviously horrifying,” said Melanie Sloan, the chairman of the “Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington” association (an organization aiming to combat corruption in U.S. parliamentary and government circles), a group of lawyers who have brought various charges against Mr. Ensign to court.
"This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, chief defender of Mr. Ensign, said in an interview that he had received a phone call from a prosecutor on Monday and another the next day, informing him that the ministry would not bring charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's defenders had cooperated with prosecutors to convince them that, as his office repeated in a statement on Wednesday, the senator had "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to explain in more detail the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutors.
"I'm not going to go into the details of the conversation between the Ministry of Justice and me, but we think we've made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to end the investigation into a separate lawsuit by the ethics group, according to which a payment of $96,000 from Mr. Ensign’s parents to the Hamptons violated the federal election law.
The election commission said there was not enough evidence that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a large Nevada company that supported the senator for a long time, was one of the companies where Mr. Hampton found lobbyist work thanks to the help of Mr. Ensign.
An email from December 2008 proves that after the company continued Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensing's chief of staff, John Lopez, had a conversation with Mr. Hampton in which he informed him that he was "buttoning" at the Department of the Interior for one thing.
Mr. Ensign also had lunch with Mr. Hampton and another customer from Nevada, Allegiant Air, and asked the Minister of Transport to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Mr. Hampton for lobbying.
When information about this affair first came to the public last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his voters and gave up his position in the Senate, where he had been fourth in the ranks of Republicans.
After noticing for many months, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he was seeking a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign is no longer the target of police investigations, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hopes that the Ethics Commission will very quickly follow the example of the Ministry of Justice and stop its investigations.
"Senator Ensign is looking forward to continuing his hard work in the service of the people of Nevada," she said.
