Can politeness connect the separating thing?
After a campaign of libel and negativity, little courtesy broke out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of a genuine two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before you quickly return to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and Congressional leaders brought no breakthrough in the big issues that had to be dealt with during the so-called “lame duck session”, the session at the end of a government period in which no more decisions are made.
After all what you hear, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor an observance of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a partisan point-gathering.
The public meeting of the President’s Deficit Commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that persist between members.
It seems clear that a close interaction over a period of months creates a mutual respect that obscures the ideological divide that continues to separate members.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - in which one of them demands from the other a sign of willingness to cooperate and compromise, while one tries to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a new party war.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it is about taxes, donations, health or expectations, the two sides are miles away from each other.
Last but not least, the November election in Washington voted mildly for at least a short time.
“No question, the tone has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration who is now working for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after elections.
Elections awaken partial passions that are dying again.
And that's good."
On some issues, especially those on the agenda of the “lame duck session,” Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution.”
Bush’s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one supports it.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or all of them, whether temporary or permanent.
Similarly, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, albeit only because Republicans cannot afford to believe the favored tax cuts for the rich while denying support to unemployed workers.
After the meeting on Tuesday at the White House, the optimism has risen that one can agree on these issues during the "lame duck session" and at the same time also ratify the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of Brookings Institute warns that successful collaboration on urgent issues of the lame duck session" does not necessarily lead to permanent cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what is happening from today until 2012, as a pre-match, or shadow boxing, for the 2012 main event," he said.
The reasons for this have much to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their formation.
No matter how concerned the Republican leaders may be about being too high poker, they know they need to try to keep their promises, cut government spending and override health reform.
These party lines are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include tax reform and the raising of some taxes as well as the raising of the retirement age and the lowering of government spending.
Deputy Chairman Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have urged so much to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan an official recommendation and they are fighting very hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the panel, since in financial matters, at least today, there is little room for manoeuvre or little sympathy for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the struggle between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place next year in the form of party clashes when Republicans challenge Obama regarding the state budget, taxes and health system, followed later by a phase of greater two-party cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partiality of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties must pay attention to the public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek the compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a larger ideological divide between Obama and the Congressional Republicans than they were between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a pure prelude to a far broader election in 2012.
From this point of view, the politeness shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the questions that still separate the two.
