Without wanting to reduce the abilities of German pilot and world champion Sebastian Vettel or the power of Renault’s engine, the “secret weapon” that the Multi Siemens Red Bull put into its hands, and thus created a winning team, has become a legend.
In reality, it is a powerful software for simulating processes that the German company launched in 2007 for purposes not related to car racing.
This computer program, known as PLM, has been used for the development of assembly chains in factories around the world, power plants and high-precision instruments.
The purpose is to faithfully reproduce or simulate a product or process before it is actually built in order to avoid errors and unnecessary costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan’s most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens’ industrial department, explains that with the use of this software in the Formula 1 factory Red Bull “in a few hours, almost in real time” can design and execute the changes and improvements that are detected on the races and in the tests.
Russwurm explains that in 1992, on average, ten technicians worked in the racing stables, who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements in a season.
Today, Red Bull’s team employs 180 highly qualified young people, who use powerful computer systems to carry out analyses and all sorts of changes to the racing car.
The Siemens manager said the PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all components of Red Bull’s racing cars, with the exception of the engine for which Renault is solely responsible.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are changed.
The changes can be transferred from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality within less than 24 hours thanks to advanced production facilities and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit to this crazy technical perfectionism is the $40 million a Formula 1 team can spend on its races in a season.
Red Bull has built its high-tech factory for the development and manufacture of its racing cars in a location 50 kilometers from London.
These are two buildings in which visits - especially by journalists - are severely restricted.
All that happens is top secret.
The workforce includes 580 people, including the two pilots, world champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
But Red Bull's true Formula 1 hero is undoubtedly the newest world champion Sebastian Vetell.
Behind the enormous technological resources that the energy drink manufacturer puts at the service of its participation on the racetracks, are other protagonists, whose support is invaluable and whose notoriety is zero.
The plant’s chief technologist, Steve Nevey, stresses that five years ago, it was still possible to say that R&D advances contributed 50 percent to the victory for racing cars and that the pilots were responsible for the rest.
Today, the share values have changed, with the technology accounting for 85 percent of the success, while the pilots’ contribution is estimated at 15 percent.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel and Webber can never be replaced by computer because they “are unpredictable gladiators.”
