Sabadell wants to 'claw' its rival one million customers in three years
Banco Sabadell’s executive board member, Jaime Guardiola, is more optimistic than other managers. He believes that 2001 will be a tough year for the banks, but initially rejects a new liquidity crisis and predicts the end of the debt war.
Nevertheless, it anticipates a drop in interest rates, which banks are trying to offset by increases in fees and loan prices.
Sabadell expects to capture one million private customers in three years - a subject that is still too existing.
Sabadell has found a way to exploit the next three years, and thus to survive in a very complicated economic environment.
The Bank will introduce a new three-year guidance plan in 2011.
The goal is not only to survive without using public aid from the FROB, but also to increase the market share by one million private customers - 700 000 if you deduct the customers that the bank will lose - which is the big challenge that this bank faces, because so far it has paid more attention to its business customers than its private customers.
This year, it has added 250,000 private customers and 50,000 businesses.
Their market share for private customers is 3.5 percent, while business customers make up more than 10 percent.
Another principle of the 2011-2013 business plan is to increase productivity, i.e. austerity, cost reduction. The challenges facing the bank will be presented together with the annual financial report.
Few banks dare to set and publish targets in these difficult times, as the financial crisis has confused all the banks’ plans around the world.
Sabadell will complete its four-year Optima Guidance Plan this year, initially designed to last three years, but due to the market situation, it was extended by one financial year.
The customers who will leave the savings banks are the main goal of the bank.
At a breakfast organized by the APIE, Guardiola stressed that 2011 would be a "difficult" year "with a long range".
The manager assumes that Spain would only be "slow" out of the crisis.
Moreover, it would be "very difficult" to "create work" in two or three years - fundamental to the survival of the banks.
Even if it assumes that the war on liabilities – which punishes the interest margins – will flow, the risk surcharges that banks and savings banks have to pay for their liquidity-retaining emissions will already be rolled down to the price of loans as a compensation for dwindling profit margins.
“The issues of liquidity and financing are structural and they will put pressure on the loans.”
"We didn't turn off the tap, but the interest rate differentials are very high," Guardiola admitted.
Banesto already issued the order to its branch network on Thursday to restrict the allocation of long-term loans and increase interest rate differentials (cf. Cinco D<0xC3><0xAD>as of 22 and 27 November).
The manager also admitted that the banks were currently pursuing the stategie of "increasing fees", but "within a competitive framework".
Sabadell’s strategy is based on organic growth, even if, as always, the group does not exclude corporate business.
It is not for nothing that he assures that in Spain "greater companies are necessary."
“Everything will change next year,” he said.
He stresses that the need for capital is currently "enormously increasing" and does not exclude that some Spanish financial institutions will slip into red numbers.
He believes that the FROB can replace the money market in capital increases.
After reassuring that Sabadell could also survive a temporary closure of the markets, he disproves the argument of some bankers who are already predicting a new liquidity crisis.
He stressed that nothing could be circulated, but unlike the incidents in June, short-term financing could be achieved through repo transactions and thus intercepted the crisis.
