Zapatero and the Red Line of Germany
Berlin has opted for the retention of the euro, but at the same time set conditions for the entire European Union.
Tensions in the markets have triggered a double response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Zapatero has introduced new adjustment measures, ranging from tax reductions for small and micro-enterprises, the regulation of temporary workers, or the lifting of the 426 euros of support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatisation of 49 percent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former government president Felipe Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible, who has summoned the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel’s position is not a mistake of her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany takes a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of most of its partners.
Given the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: A strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the German Mark - although this sounds more like science fiction at the moment - is supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a transformation of the euro according to German proposals, which means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of the countries that exceed the requirements; possibly the cessation of payments by some countries, as well as the expansion of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been going on for some time now, so there are no excuses.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled out a constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016 onwards.
This was the first sign of the divergence between what Germany considered necessary (strong tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was put forward by the Central European country, when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the published opinion were absolutely against the salvation of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel comes out with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union agreements to enable the rescue of a country while at the same time obliging private lenders to bear some of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it was driving the Ireland crisis and all that followed.
However, their proposal, albeit slightly sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will participate in the reform of the European Union, which is intended to enable these measures from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures have to be taken now - there will be no longer the old functioning of the euro from this date on.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area, in which the conflicting countries will be severely punished, can be forced to declare themselves insolvent, and in this case the private sector will have to pay some of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to take a hard course of growth, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness as well as positive foreign trade balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as it was led by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would be bad at not understanding it.
It is not just about reducing the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will be more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities that are offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this too, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the major companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in his own house has prepared its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn’t look like it would change anything.
Among the possibilities considered, the fact that we would have to leave the euro area, which is full of little-reputable countries, is not to be ruled out.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it had warned us.
Sports and circumvention
Tricks like that of Alonso and Ramos in the game against Ajax show inventive spirit, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League resulted in a lot of ink being shed over whether it was an unsportsmanlike action or not and whether both players should possibly be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will meet the prescribed sanction in the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club’s coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provoking a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos – the unwritten but adhered to rules in this sport.
Part of the emergent debate about the case is due to a team from football club Real Madrid (who in his anthem pretended to be noble and honorable and on other occasions had punished his players for similar incidents) playing the lead role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behavior, which is not explicitly prohibited by the statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute a rule circumvention. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the infringing players take unwarranted advantage from the opposing team.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually mean by cheating or rule bypassing, because the bypassing of the rule was not done secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible to be punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders drew from the deliberate fouls.
It should be emphasized here that the rival was neither put in a more unfavorable position nor benefits were demanded for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, as the club then does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term, to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually retire as well, and with this approach, players get a sanction and transition into the second card cycle, in which they exit with a card less than in the first cycle because of card accumulation.
It is not clear if this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the sporting spirit, which includes strategic decisions to make the most of the regulations.
In this case, players did not want to circumvent sanctions (this would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they rather wanted to choose when to undergo them.
They made a strategic decision without evading a penalty or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and the control environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemic arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transmission.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
