Pakistan's nuclear program raises serious concern in the US
Islamabad produces nuclear weapons "faster than any other country".
Wikileaks revelations confirm relations between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the North American embassy in Pakistan and the U.S. State Department, revealed by the Wikileaks internet portal, confirms the enormous concerns the Pakistani nuclear program Washington is raising.
On the fringe of the clarification and juicy details provided by the documents on the content of the talks and the mindset of accredited North American diplomats in Islamabad, these reveal that cooperation between the two countries in terms of nuclear security is not strengthened, but on the contrary "decreases", and that the unstable Asian country produces more nuclear weapons "to a faster rhythm than any other country".
In particular, the peculiarity of the Pakistani nuclear program—that the weapons are not assembled, but their individual parts are stored in order to make their destruction more difficult in the event of a possible attack—are preparing Washington for sleepless nights.
The Pakistani ambassador Anne W. Patterson noted the following risks in a report prior to the visit of the former head of the National Security Council, James Jones: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to the area under attack by the Taliban, the suspected dispersion of nuclear material and the vulnerability of the transport of nuclear material."
The large number of people implicated in the nuclear arsenals and missile programs is no longer considered by the United States, but also by Russia, to be excessive and reason to exercise caution.
“Pakistan must hire rigorously faithful personnel to guard the nuclear facilities; due to the low level of education and culture, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recluse individuals working on nuclear or missile programs,” said Yuri Korolev, an expert at the Russian Foreign Ministry, in a meeting with his North American counterparts.
New to the documentary unveiled by Julian Assange’s internet portal is that US-Pakistan cooperation on nuclear proliferation is declining and the increased pace at which Pakistan produces nuclear weapons.
In May, an embassy office describing communication with Pakistan as "frustrating" explains: "Often there is no transparency; on aid offers we do not receive answers or they are rejected."
In another communication, Peter Lavoy, a state intelligence official for South Asia, confirms that "despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons as quickly as any other country."
Ambassador Patterson asked Washington during a visit to the Chief of Army, General Ashfaq Kayani, to "clarify" to the person in charge that "Pakistan's army has to stop its tacit support of terrorist groups."
Searching for Wikileaks chief
Obama appoints a high level of responsibility for the anti-terrorism struggle to prevent new revelations.
Interpol issued a red warning on the persecution and detection of Assange.
Everything related to Wikileaks and its founder, Jullian Assange, forms a complicated labyrinth in which it is difficult to clarify the facts.
Yesterday, Interpol issued a "red warning" about the "discovery and persecution" of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest order.
It’s not new, it’s from November 20th.
It also has nothing to do with the last revelation of over four million U.S. diplomatic documents, but with the allegations of sexual abuse facing the Australian in Sweden.
WikiLeaks founder Mark Stephens also assured the police “know where and how to contact Mr. Assange.”
Already on the 20th, the international police agency based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but it was not announced until yesterday after receiving the authority by the Swedish authorities.
The 188 Interpol countries are instructed to identify and locate Assange, "to arrest him for the time being and hand him over."
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red warning, many member countries consider the red warning as a free letter for an arrest - which must be carried out by the national police - especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case for Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be staying.
The action outraged Assange’s lawyers, who published a letter yesterday informing them that the 39-year-old founder of Wikileaks is ready to answer the Swedish authorities’ questions via video conference.
They also recall that Assange requested the departure from Sweden and was given the appropriate approval by the prosecutor, who is compared to the legendary Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin’s security chief.
"This is like a hunt, not a legal prosecution," the letter said.
While the world is looking for him - and his mother from Australia asserts her son's innocence - Assange stays in an unknown place, but not in silence.
On Monday, he gave an interview to the head of Time magazine via Skype from an indefinite location, during which he requested the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
“If it can be proven that she was responsible for ordering North American diplomats to spy on the UN and thus violated international agreements signed by the US, she would have to resign,” he said.
His opinion was condemned yesterday by the White House press secretary, Robert Gibbs, who described the request for resignation as "laughing and absurd."
“I’m not sure why we should value the opinion of a guy with a website,” he told CNN.
Obama himself has commissioned a senior anti-terrorism campaigner, Rusell Travers, to prevent new document disclosures.
President Barack Obama’s attempt to pay less attention to Assange is contrary to the opinions that conservative politicians and commentators proclaim these days.
Congressman Peter King, who will chair the National Security Committee of the House of Representatives from January, has called on the State Department to investigate the possibility of putting Wikileaks on the list of terrorist organizations "to seize their funds and pursue anyone who supports or contributes to them."
Tom Flanagan, adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, had gone even further, and he had to revoke his statement that Assange must be "murdered".
"Obama would have to turn it into a target and use an unmanned plane or something."
Those who did not apologize were Mike Huckabee, Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and potential presidential candidate.
"Whoever it was who leaked information into the government is guilty of treason and anything that is not execution is too mild a punishment," he told Fox.
