China upholds its greenhouse gas reduction targets
The representative of China said at COP16 that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and would maintain its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China will keep its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, assures Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations Climate Change Summit (COP16), Su Wei reassured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
In the past four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work with the international community on this matter.
He explained that the Chinese climate change strategy is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which includes the targets for reducing emissions of gases, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, the state authorities have worked with those of the central state and municipalities to achieve the energy saving, energy efficiency and emissions reduction targets.
In addition, he stated that several multi-year plans have already been initiated or completed, both those financed by the Chinese government and those that received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the programme for the effective use of energy, which was introduced over the last five years and had received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and from private hands.
There is also a provincial-level project on climate change, another to replace traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs, and another to mitigate and adapt.
Martin Krol, a scientific adviser to the government on climate change in this country, confirmed that China’s efforts are far greater than would be generally assumed.
He showed that the per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons. China is responsible for a 9% overall contribution to pollution.
It is also making unprecedented progress in the field of energy use, with energy efficiency increased by twenty percent over the past five years, and another goal is to be achieved by 2020, he said.
