The U.S. amends the rules for obtaining a visa
Persons must present themselves to the consulate for visa application before their conversation with the service agencies; costs will be shortened in this way.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa in the Embassy of the United States and in the Consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves to the visa application service bodies (ASC, the initial letters in English) before their conversation in the consulate.
The ASC staff shall record the applicant’s biometric data, which shall be reviewed by the Consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa is reduced because it is no longer necessary to pay separately the appointment agreement, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over.
The applicant makes only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the counter value to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for traders and investors.
Those who just want to renew their visa do not need to have a conversation in the consulate, they only need to introduce themselves to the nearest ASC, where they present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Since the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second date for the conversation in the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the $26 service surcharge.
Additional information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
