The U.S. National Aerospace Agency (NASA) announces an astrobiological discovery tomorrow, Thursday, that could confirm the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented at a press conference at NASA’s Washington headquarters tomorrow at 13.00 a.m. by experts in astrobiology, a science that examines the origin, development, distribution and future of life in the universe.
On convening the press conference, NASA reassured that it would present “a supervisory find for the search for extraterrestrial life,” triggering speculation among experts from other countries.
The discovery could prove the theory that human-like creatures could exist in hostile environments that were previously thought to be uninhabitable. It was hypothesized that if their living conditions improved, they could turn into intelligent beings like humans.
Apparently, it is a microbe found on the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, living in an environment considered too toxic to all imaginable life forms, as the lake is heavily arsenic.
In some way, the microbial uses arsenic as a survival resource, and taking this ability into account, the chances are that there could be similar life on other planets that do not have our protective atmosphere.
When these organisms metabolize arsenic, according to astrobiologists, it is proven that "there is actually a different life form, a second life form that is different from the one we know."
The space agency will announce the actual reach of its find at the press conference tomorrow, Thursday.
The conference is attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars, and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who studies Titan (Saturn’s largest moon) on whether its chemical composition is similar to Earth.
