Global plan for the renewal of lighting
The UN yesterday in Cancun proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (FCC) equivalent to nearly a third of the additional reduction that needs to be implemented to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments from developed countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of CFCs emitted to the earth due to lighting, if the white-hot bulbs, which still represent a 50 to 70% monopoly on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or even better by light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emissions emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans designed to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt would still have to be deducted from this balance to stabilize the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020, to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white-hot bulbs 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED light bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced twice as much.
The compact phosphor bulbs last on average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as the ones that the manufacturer Philips launched this week - this company, by the way, participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-hot bulb, suggesting the savings potential of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely novel light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistor.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact phosphor bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they must therefore be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the producers provide an acceptance point.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet, according to the report, is not the compact phosphor bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit significantly more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would generate thanks to this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year on the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, whose construction would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
