Revenge hackers and embittered spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double meaning.
On one side, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and gives a foretaste of the future dominated by regression.
But let's do it in turn.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirming the fact that each file created by an intelligence service (an x-any nation) is made up exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits are nothing more than what has been read in any X-journal for months anyway (except those whose owner is Berlusconi), and Gaddafi's terrifyingly caricatured profile has been providing cabaret artists with fabric for their sketch for a long time.
The rule that the secret dossiers can only consist of known news is essential for the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not only in this century.
When you go to a library dedicated to esotherical publications, you will realize that every work (about the Grail, the Mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars, or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (yet because he does not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism do not believe in anything other than what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown’s success mechanism.
As well as the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or restricted mind) is also the head of the intelligence service (otherwise he could be whatever, for example, an editor at Libération), who only considers what he acknowledges to be true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department was the same as those that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why was such an uproar made about the revelations of these dossiers?
On one side, these say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies - at least since the end of World War II and since then the heads of government can call each other or take an airplane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and have turned into espionage centers, with the exception of a few small representation tasks.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that you do so to ignore it.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that an X-any hacker can tap into the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world carries the significant blow against the prestige of the State Department.
In addition, the scandal puts less the victims, rather the "sharp judges" in trouble.
But let us dedicate ourselves to the profound nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell’s time, all power could be bundled like a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy could have turned out to be perfectly correct since then, where you can control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction you make, the hotel you visit, the highway you choose, and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But if you consider what is going on today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control gait ceases to be unilaterally directed and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the citizen's avenger - can discover the secrets of power.
But how can a power that is no longer able to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free of secrets, as it reveals the public sphere; but in the style of WikiLeaks, revealing any secrets of Hillary Clinton's power to be empty secrets.
WikiLeaks has not wronged Sarkozy or Merkel, but Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this resentment that has been inflicted on such a tremendous power?
It is obvious that the states will no longer put any reserved information online in the future – that would be equivalent to a signage glued to the street corner.
But it’s just as obvious that with current technologies, it’s in vain to hope that confidential reports can be kept secret over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state has moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private relationships be maintained in the future and only for certain ears?
I know very well that my prediction sounds science-fiction and romantic at the moment, but I see myself compelled to introduce myself to the government agents, secretly moving emphatically on uncontrollable march routes, carrying their messages nowhere else but in mere memory, and moreover hiding the few written information they have received in shoe sales.
The information would be stored in a single copy in closed drawers: basically, Watergate’s espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is progressing like a cancer these days, namely backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet reconstructed a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analogous) video cassettes had allowed film researchers to explore a film band by band by spinning from the back to the front and uncovering all the secrets of the assembly, while the (numeric) CDs nowadays allow nothing more than jumping from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro portions.
High-speed trains travel from Rome to Milan within three hours, while it takes three and a half hours by plane, including transfers.
It is therefore not unusual that politics and communication technology come back on car and horse.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the messages.
At present, it is the messages that demand confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France makes its financial promises beautiful
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to investigate compliance with the fast-start (also known as early-start) financing promises implemented by developing countries.
And already the coarse French fairies have been uncovered.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries have pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years, France 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU has drawn all registers to convince its partners of their commitment to fast-start financing: detailed action report from their Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and appreciated for its true value: developing countries and civil society would like to see all developed countries doing the same thing at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track to respect its 7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But when you look at the details, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" to ensure that additional use has been made without being detrimental to public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what “new and additional” means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the indicative value that they consider best.
The EU Commission, for example, has chosen as a benchmark for those of 2009: international financing will be maintained, and will add 150 million to the Fast-Start funding over three years.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or conditions at the level of public development aid.
In return, France felt that the financing of “all new projects” of 2010 was “new and additional”.
In other words, there are no benchmarks for the expenditure of the previous year or at the global level of public development aid.
Concretely, the total amount of French aid to developing countries may remain stable (or may decrease) - France claims to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule on this, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, include 1 borrowed € equivalent to 1 donated €.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often emission mitigation projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro that is received as an equivalent for a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan should be counted as a commitment for the lender country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing but the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking up 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million euros - see also the EU document to convince itself.
France is the only country in the EU that uses large amounts of loans.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are 100% committed to donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to fulfill its obligations, France only spends 10 cents and understands a comparable commitment.
Nice hocus pocus!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double dizziness: in part with a further development of the action over time and in the other part with the reality of financial commitment.
France manages to believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" millions in line with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Treasury (as it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a double negative effect; once EU-internal (why the other member states continue to donate if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries do not let themselves be completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing is only a small question in a relatively short time compared to the whole of discussions on climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let's hope this isn't the case.
In any case, it is indispensable to learn his lesson from this first year of premature financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and of balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could bring forward discussions on the subject of long-term financing (another, decisive and currently debated topic): one does not escape the question of "accountability" or the accounting method of its loans.
France could change its position in order to be as progressive in matters of dispute as it is in other matters.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France’s fast-start and its vision of “accountability” as well as the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - pesticides taken by children
A 10-year-old child takes 81 different chemical substances over the course of the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Association Générations Futures (former movement to protect the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which explains that its results "do not represent a statistically significant value given the small number of samples analysed, but rather represent an illustrative character of the problem addressed", had bought the foodstuffs usually consumed by a 10-year-old child at meals between July and September, plus a snack in the supermarkets in Oise and Paris.
These typical meals – including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit portions, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day – have been studied, as have laboratories looking for chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is devastating: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as potentially or likely to be carcinogenic and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances with endocrinin disruption factor, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical, individually taken substance are not exceeded in the approximate totality of cases, this survey shows very well that the reality in which the consumer is exposed to potentially carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrinin disruption is alarming," notes the association.
Already at breakfast alone, butter and tea with milk already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three safely proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as an intermediate meal for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, including lunch, where the study found traces of an insecticide strictly prohibited in the EU.
In addition, the steak, the tuna from the can, even the baguette and the chewing gum of pesticides and other chemicals were also spiked.
In tap water, the analyses have revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak with 34 determined chemical residues was the "richest", and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unloaded.
The final risk of this "poison cocktail" for the consumer "will likely be undervalued," the study said.
The "Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts" (EE-LV), in turn, has proposed "in view of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase in civilizational diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified references to the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
